        "assistant": "**Prismatic affinity** differs from **perspectivism** or **perspective-dependence** because it is not merely about *where* an observer is positioned, but about *how* the object is attended to or framed.\n\nIn ordinary perspective-dependence, the object remains the same, but its appearance varies with viewpoint:\n\n- From one angle, a cube shows two faces.\n- From another angle, it shows three faces.\n- The descriptions differ, but they are understood as partial views of the same stable object.\n\nIn **prismatic affinity**, the shift is deeper: the object’s **apparent identity** changes coherently depending on the observer’s angle of attention. Two observers may produce descriptions that are not just different perspectives on the same thing, but **non-overlapping yet internally consistent accounts** of what the object is.\n\nSo the distinction is:\n\n- **Perspective-dependence:** “We see the same thing from different positions.”\n- **Prismatic affinity:** “We attend to the same object under different framings, and it becomes coherently different things.”\n\nPerspective-dependence is spatial or positional.  \nPrismatic affinity is attentional, interpretive, or framing-based.\n\nFor example, a building may look narrow from one street and wide from another; that is perspective-dependence. But if one observer attends to it as a sacred monument, another as a political symbol, and another as an engineering system—each producing a coherent but non-overlapping identity—that would be closer to prismatic affinity.",
