        "assistant": "**Prismatic affinity** differs from **polysemy** because polysemy is about a **word, sign, or symbol having multiple related meanings**, while prismatic affinity is about a **perceived object whose apparent identity shifts with the angle of attention**.\n\nIn **polysemy**, the meanings are usually understood as belonging to the same term or sign:\n\n- “Head” can mean the head of a body, the head of a table, the head of an organization, or the head of a river.\n- These meanings are different but related.\n- Context selects which sense is active.\n\nIn **prismatic affinity**, the issue is not that a word has several related meanings. Rather, the object itself is apprehended differently under different framings, producing descriptions that may be **non-overlapping but internally consistent**.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Polysemy:** one sign has multiple related senses.\n- **Prismatic affinity:** one perceived object yields coherently different apparent identities depending on attentional framing.\n\nA polysemous term carries a cluster of meanings.  \nA prismatically affine object changes what it seems to be under different modes of attention.\n\nFor example, if the word “field” means an agricultural field, a field of study, or a magnetic field, that is **polysemy**. But if the same physical site is attended to by one observer as an ecosystem, by another as ancestral land, and by another as real estate—each producing a coherent but non-overlapping account of what the site *is*—that would be closer to **prismatic affinity**.",
